EasyVisa Project¶

Context:¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired your firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information for the employee's continent of residence
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee have any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

OBSERVATIONS

The data has 25480 rows and 12 columns (series) total with no nulls and no duplicated values.

  • 9 columns of type object
  • 2 columns of type int64
  • 1 columns of type float64

No null values exist in the dataset/so we do not need to perform NaN or fillna.() activities.

We have two series that can be converted to a boolean for our analysis later.

  • case_status: Denied/Certified
  • full_time_position: Y/N
  • requires_job_training: Y/N
  • has_job_experience: Y/N

We have several series that will likely be treated as dummy variables:

  • continent: Asia/Africa/North America/Europe/South America/Oceania
  • education_of_employee: High School/Master's/"Bachelor's/Doctorate
  • region_of_employment: West/Northeast/South/Midwest/Island
  • unit_of_wage: Hour/Year/Week/Month

The series no_of_employees has a very wide range of -26 to 602,069. We may need to examine outliers in our EDA analysis. Similarly, prevailing_wage ranges from 2 to 319,210.

The data is highly skewed for our continuous series:

  • no_of_employees (right skewed, likely due to excessive range of data)
  • yr_of_estab (left skewed)
  • prevailing_wage (right skewed, with an unusually high numer of low values, and some right-skewness

# Function to get counts and percentages for categorical values

def get_value_counts(df, column_name):
    ''' Function to get value counts and percentages'''

    value_counts = df[column_name].value_counts()
    value_percentages = df[column_name].value_counts(normalize=True)

    return value_counts, value_percentages

# Function to exclude outliers by including specific percentiles

def cap_values_by_percent(df, column_name, min, max):
    '''
    Cap a DataFrame column to only include values between the 25th and 75th percentiles.

    df: pandas DataFrame
    column_name: column to be capped
    '''

    # Calculate the 25th and 75th percentiles
    q_min = df[column_name].quantile(min)
    q_max = df[column_name].quantile(max)

    # Filter the DataFrame to only include values between the 25th and 75th percentiles
    capped_df = df[(df[column_name] >= q_min) & (df[column_name] <= q_max)]

    return capped_df

# Function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.

def print_histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 8), kde=False, bins=None, showfliers=None):
    '''
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    '''

    # Create two subplots
    f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,      # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be the same for all subplots
        gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # Create boxplot and add triangle at mean value
    if showfliers:
      sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color='blue', showfliers=showfliers)
    else:
      sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color='blue')

    # Create histogram
    if bins:
      if showfliers:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, bins=bins, showfliers=showfliers)
      else:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, bins=bins)
    else:
      if showfliers:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, showfliers=showfliers)
      else:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist)

    # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color='green', linestyle='--')
    # Add median to the histogram
    ax_hist.axvline(data[feature].median(), color='black', linestyle='-')

# Function to print a histogram with several controllable options, including hue, size and title
def print_histogram(data, column, width, height, titleText, hue=None, bins=None, method='auto'):
  ''' Print a single, sorted histogram with title and labels and optional hue'''

  # set figure size and title
  plt.figure(figsize=(width, height))
  plt.title(titleText)
  plt.xticks(rotation=90)

  # dynamically set the hue if passed in
  if hue == None:
    sns.histplot(data=data,x=column, legend=False);
  else:
    sns.histplot(data=data,x=column, hue=column, legend=False);

  # dynamically set bins
  if bins is None:
      if method == 'auto':
        bins = 'auto'
      else:
        bins = method

# Function to print a bar chart with counts
def print_simple_count_barplot(data, x_column, width, height, titleText):
  ''' Print a line chart plot '''

  # Compute value counts of column
  category_counts = df[x_column].value_counts()

  # Convert Series to DataFrame and reset index
  df_counts = category_counts.reset_index()

  # Rename columns for clarity
  df_counts.columns = ['category', 'count']

  # Plotting with Seaborn
  plt.figure(figsize=(width, height))
  ax = sns.barplot(data=df_counts, x=df_counts['category'], y=df_counts['count'], palette='viridis', hue=df_counts['category'], legend=False)

  # Turn off grid
  ax.grid(False)

  # Add labels and title
  plt.xlabel(x_column)
  plt.xticks(rotation=90)
  plt.ylabel('Count')
  plt.title(titleText)

# Function to print a bar chart with counts - displaying counts on top of bars
def print_simple_labeled_count_barplot(data, x_column, width, height, titleText):
    '''Print a bar chart plot with counts on top of each bar.'''

    # Compute value counts of column
    category_counts = df[x_column].value_counts()

    # Convert Series to DataFrame and reset index
    df_counts = category_counts.reset_index()

    # Rename columns for clarity
    df_counts.columns = ['category', 'count']

    # Plotting with Seaborn
    plt.figure(figsize=(width, height))
    ax = sns.barplot(data=df_counts, x=df_counts['category'], y=df_counts['count'], palette='viridis', hue=df_counts['category'], legend=False)

    # Turn off grid
    ax.grid(False)

    # Annotate bars with counts
    for p in ax.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(f'{int(height)}',
                    (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., height),
                    ha='center',
                    va='center',
                    xytext=(0, 5),
                    textcoords='offset points',
                    fontsize=10,
                    color='black')


    # Add labels and title
    plt.xlabel(x_column)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title(titleText)

# This function prints a stacked bar plot
def print_stacked_barplot(data, indexCol, xCol, width, height, titleText):
  """ Print a stacked barplot with title and labels """

  # Create a pivot table to count booking_status by market_segment
  pivot_df = data.pivot_table(index=indexCol, columns=xCol, aggfunc='size', fill_value=0)

  # Plotting
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(width, height))

  # Stacked bar chart
  pivot_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax)

  # Set labels and title
  ax.set_xlabel(xCol)
  ax.set_ylabel(indexCol)
  ax.set_title(titleText)

  # Rotate x-axis labels for better visibility if needed
  plt.xticks(rotation=45)

  # Show plot
  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

# This function prints a heatmap for two categorical variables

def plot_heatmap(data, x_column, y_column):
    '''
    Plot a heatmap showing the occurrence counts for each combination of two categorical variables.

    df: pandas DataFrame
    x_col: column name for x-axis (categorical variable)
    y_col: column name for y-axis (categorical variable)
    '''
    # Create a pivot table with counts
    pivot_table = df.pivot_table(index=y_column, columns=x_column, aggfunc='size', fill_value=0)

    # Plot heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(pivot_table, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='YlGnBu', cbar=True)
    plt.title(f'Heatmap of {y_column} vs {x_column}')
    plt.xlabel(x_column)
    plt.ylabel(y_column)
    plt.show()

    'N': 0,
    'Y': 1
}
df_eda['requires_job_training_int'] = df_eda['requires_job_training'].map(requires_job_training_mapping)

# Create an integer for has_job_experience and map values
has_job_experience_mapping = {
    'N': 0,
    'Y': 1
}
df_eda['has_job_experience_int'] = df_eda['has_job_experience'].map(has_job_experience_mapping)


# Create a new value for higher education and map values
education_of_employee_mapping = {
    "High School": 0,
    "Bachelor's":  1,
    "Master's":    2,
    "Doctorate":   3,
}
df_eda['education_of_employee_int'] = df_eda['education_of_employee'].map(education_of_employee_mapping)


# Add an index
df_eda['id'] = df_eda.index

  elif mean < median and abs(this_range) >= 1 and abs(this_range) <= 2:

  if mean > median and abs(this_range) >= 2:
    print(' * Distribution is skewed to the right.', end='')
  elif mean < median and abs(this_range) >= 2:
    print(' * Distribution is skewed to the left.', end='')

OBSERVATIONS

Continent

  • Most applicants are located in Asia (16861, or 66%)
  • Europe (15%) and North America (13%) have about the same number of applicants, but still only about 1/4 of the number present in Asia.

Education

  • Most applicants (about 20K in our set) have some degree of higher education.

    • 38% have Master's degrees
    • 40% have Bachelor's degrees
    • 13% have a high school education
    • 9% have Doctorate degrees

  • The dataset does not include any applicants with less than a high school education

Job Experience

  • Slightly more applicants (14K, or 58%) have job experience than not (10K, or 42%), although the numbers are fairly evenly split.

Requires Job Training

  • Most applicants (22.5K, or 88%) do not require job training.

Region of Employment

  • Northeast, South and West are the most commonly desired employment regions.

  • Midwest has fewer applications, but more than Island regions.

    • Northeast: 28%
    • South: 28%
    • West: 26%
    • Midwest: 17%
    • Island: 1%

Unit of Wage

  • Most applications (over 90%) are geared toward positions with a yearly income.
  • Very few applications exist for hourly, monthly or weekly wages (less than 10%).

Full Time Position

  • Most applicants (almost 90%) desire full-time positions, while very few (less than 10%) are seeking other work arrangements.

Case Status

  • One-third of the current applications were denied, while two thirds were certified.

OBSERVATIONS: BIVARIATE ANALYSIS

With regard to case_status, it appears that level of education, job experience and prevailing wages are all important features when it comes to certifying visa applications. We will investigate this later during our model construction.

Job Experience:

  • Applicants with job experience are nearly twice as likely to be certified (11,024 certified vs. 5994 denied, who had experience)
  • Applicants who were denied were nearly as likely to be denied whether they have job experience or not (3778 certified vs. 4684 denied, who did not have experience).

Education:

  • Denials occur for all levels of education.
  • Very few doctoral applicants are denied.

  • More denials occur for high-school only educated applicants.

  • Certified

    • Bachelor's: 6367
    • Doctorate: 1912
    • High School: 1164
    • Master's: 75751
  • Denied
    • Bachelor's: 3867
    • Doctorate: 280
    • High School: 2256
    • Master's: 2059

Prevailing Wage:

  • The range of prevailing wages is similar for both Certified and Denied applications
  • Average prevailing wages for Certified applicants is 77,293.
  • Average prevailing wages for Denied applicants is slightly lower, at 68,748.
  • Even though the range of wages is similar for both full time and non-full time, the average prevailling wages differ.
    • Average prevailing wages for full time positions: 70,855
    • Average prevailing wages for non-full time positions 104,745
      • Similarly, we see that wages for applicants requiring training is slightly higher than for applications not requiring job training.
    • Average prevailing wages for applications requiring training: 82,467
    • Average prevailing wages for applications not requiring training: 73,404

Job Training:

  • Most applicants do not require job training
    • 43% of Certified applicants have job experience
    • 24% of Certified applicants lack experience
    • 15% of Denied applications have job experience
    • 18% of Denied applications lack job experience

Questions to Answer¶

Through our EDA and analysis, we will answer these key questions:

  • Does education play a role in Visa certification?
  • How does the visa status vary across different continents?
  • Does work experience influence visa status?
  • Which pay unit is most likely to be certified for a visa?
  • How does the visa status change with the prevailing wage?
Question 1: Does education play a role in Visa certification?¶

Those with higher education may want to travel abroad for a well-paid job.

Answer

Yes, level of education does impact whether or not an application is Certified or Denied. Over half of our Certified applicants have a Master's or Bachelor's degree.

Doctoral degrees greatly increase the odds of being Certified, and only about 1 in 7 applications are Denied (only about 1%).

Comparing by education level, high school only educated applicants are denied 66% of the time. By contrast, all other education levels have a much higher ratio of Certified to Denied results.

Answer

Question 5: How does the visa status change with the prevailing wage?¶

The US government has established a prevailing wage to protect local talent and foreign workers.

Answer

Prevailing wages do not seem to vary widely for Certified vs. Denied applicants. This makes sense, since the wages are set by the government irrespective of whether applicants are certified or denied.

  • Wage mean for Denied applications: 68,749

That said, we did find a slight correlation level of .08 between case status and prevailing wages. We should investigate this further in our model to see if this feature should be considered.

# Function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    '''
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    '''

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            'Accuracy': acc,
            'Recall': recall,
            'Precision': precision,
            'F1': f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

# This function plots a confusion_matrix for a classification model - works

def confusion_matrix_statsmodels(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    '''
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    '''
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ['{0:0.0f}'.format(item) + '\n{0:.2%}'.format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Model Construction¶

For the business case in this project, we know that our goal is to accurately predict Certified visa approvals by determining which, if any, features influence the possibility of a visa application being Certified or Denied.

Hypotheses

Null Hypothesis:

  • H0: No features have an impact on case status outcomes.

Alternative Hypothesis:

  • HA: One or more features have an impact on case status outcomes.

Model Metric

  • If the model incorrectly predicts a visa will be Certified, but it is actually Denied, we have a False Positive. The number of actual Certifications will be overstated, and visa spots may potentially be left empty if quotas exist.

  • If the model incorrectly predicts a visa will be Denied, but it is actually Certified, we have a False Negative. The number of Certifications will be higher than expected, and some people who were Certified may not have employment opportunities.

Since we want to accurately predict both scenarios, we should seek to optimize both Recall and Precision, and use the F1 Score to assess model performance. This will provide the best balance to avoid over or under-certifying applicants.

The remainder of this notebook defines diverse model types. We will construct six different types of models, assess the performance of each, tune its hyperparameters, and then evaluate all tuned models to choose our final model set.

Model Types

  • Decision Tree
  • Gradient Boost
  • AdaBoost
  • Bagging
  • Random Forest
  • XGBoost

After tuning, the training and test models performed more consistently, even though the overall F1 did not increase by much.

Bagging¶

    'n_estimators' : [30,50,70],

Summary: Untuned Models¶

  • Decision Tree and Random Forest are both overfitted, with each one yielding 100% in Accuracy, Precision, Recall and F1 scores for training, but much lower scores for test data.
  • Bagging performs similarly, at 99% in all categories for training and much lower for test data.
  • AdaBoost, GradientBoost and XGBoost all perform well and yielded similar training and test results in the 70-80% range.
  • For the well-performing models and the balanced F1 score we care most about:
    • AdaBoost gave us 82% for both training and test data.
    • Gradient Boost performed similarly, with 83% for training, and 82% for test.
    • XGBoost gave the highest F1 score, at 89% for training, but only 81% for test.

Model Tuning¶

Now that we have our base model performance, let's try to tune the models to identify proper settings and feature performance.

When tuning these models, since we are emphasizing F1 scoring, we will specify that as our scoring metric.

Hypertuning: Decision Tree (Classification)¶

In [130]:
#Tuning the decision tree

# Build estimator - original
estimator_decision_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight='balanced' ,random_state=1)

# Grid of recommended tuning parameters,
parameter_grid_dt = {
    'max_depth': np.arange(2,6),
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 4, 7],
    'max_leaf_nodes' : [10, 15],
    'min_impurity_decrease': [0.0001,0.001]
    }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - we care most about f1
scorer_dt = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj_decision_tree = GridSearchCV(
      estimator_decision_tree,
      parameter_grid_dt,
      scoring=scorer_dt
      )

# Fit the model to the data
grid_obj_decision_tree = grid_obj_decision_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the model to the best estimator parameters
tuned_model_decision_tree = grid_obj_decision_tree.best_estimator_

# Fit the tuned model to the data with best estimator
tuned_model_decision_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

Hypertuning: Bagging¶

# Tune bagging model
estimator_bagging = BaggingClassifier(random_state=1)

# Tune bagging model with an expansion, since original hyperparameters yielded disparate training and test results
estimator_expanded_bagging = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(), random_state=1)

# Grid of recommended hypertuning parameters
parameter_grid_bag = {
    'max_samples': [0.8,0.9,1],
    'max_features': [0.7,0.8,0.9],
    'n_estimators' : [30,50,70],
}

# Grid of expanded hyperparameters to see if we can further tune the model
parameter_expanded_grid_bag = {
    'base_estimator__max_depth': [5],
    'max_samples': [0.7, 0.8, 0.9],
    'max_features': [0.7, 0.8, 0.9],
    'n_estimators': [30, 50, 70]
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer_bag = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj_bagging = GridSearchCV(
      estimator_expanded_bagging,  #estimator_bagging,
      parameter_expanded_grid_bag, #parameter_grid_bag,
      scoring=scorer_bag
      )

# Fit the model to the data
grid_obj_bagging = grid_obj_bagging.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the model to the best combination of parameters
tuned_model_bagging = grid_obj_bagging.best_estimator_

# Fit the model to the data using the best estimator
tuned_model_bagging.fit(X_train, y_train)

Summary: Tuned Models¶

  • Of all the tuned models, Random Forest performed the best. In this model overfitting has been resolved, giving us a very high recall rate (97% training, 93% test) and F1 score of 86% for training, and 82% for testing.

  • AdaBoost improved slightly by a few percentage points in several categories, giving us a final F1 score of 83% for training and 82% for test.

  • Gradient Boost varied by one percentage point in several categories, but maintained its 83% training and 82% test F1 scores.

  • Bagging remained overfitted with the recommended hyperparameters. By adding a Decision Tree Classifier and expanding the parameters, we brought the results for Bagging in line with the other model results. Now, the F1 scores for Bagging match AdaBoost at 83% F1 score for training and 82% for test.

  • Decision Tree overfitting has been somewhat solved, with an F1 score of 82% and Recall score of 87%. However, the test performance in most categories is still in the low to mid 70% range.

OBSERVATIONS

We can see that certain features are statistically significant by combining the results from all models.

  • For all features with over 5% importance, all four models detected them. Two of the models, Bagging and AdaBoost, did not support generating feature importances from the models we created.

  • A high school education carried the most weight, and was detected with values between 28% and 37% weight in all four models for which we could measure features.

  • Having job experience is the second most important feature, carrying between 16% and 24% weight. All models ranked this as the second most important feature, although both Boosting algorithms weighted it lower (16% and 12%) than Decision Tree or Random Forest classifiers (24% each).

  • Three of our four models detected prevailing wage as important (12% to 13%).

  • One model detected Annual Wages as important (6% weight), although no other models did.

  • Applicants possessing a Master's Degree carried a weight between 8% and 12% in all four models.

  • Finally, a continent value of Europe carriers between 5% to 7% weight, depending on model.

  • Any feature-model combination not listed below had less than 5% feature importance.

Final Ensemble Model¶

To construct the final model, we want to compare the results of our models and pick the best-performing ones to include in our stacked ensemble model.

The chart below summarizes results by comparing each training and test run, for both tuned and untuned models. We could potentially further tune models, but with ensemble modeling, it benefits from having a collection of weak learners. Therefore we will use the tuned results.

Below, we can compare each model and run type. Fortunately, with additional hypertuning, we were able to address overfitting in each model and can now include all of the learners in our ensemble model.

We have seven different models we've identified as candidates for our ensemble model. Of these, two are untuned models whose tuned models performed similarly. This leaves us with 5 tuned models we can include.

Stacking: Ensemble Model (Tuned Model)¶

Based on our F1 scores calculated earlier, we identifed several models with consistent training and test results. We are working with a classification problem; therefore, it makes sense to use the well-performing classification base models we identified earlier.

We'll use the tuned versions of the well-performing, tuned models to construct a diverse ensemble model. In addition, since ensemble model learning benefits from as many learners as possible, we'll include the last (less performant) tuned Decision Tree model as well.

Base estimators:

  • Decision Tree Classifier
  • Random Forest Classifier
  • AdaBoost with Decision Tree Classifier
  • Gradient Boost with AdaBoost Classifier
  • Bagging with Decision Tree Classifier

Metamodel estimator:

  • XGBoost Classifier

Final Model Summary¶

Now that we've built our aggregate ensemble model, we can evaluate its performance. Let's also revisit our original analysis goal to see if our model achieves what we set out to do.

Desired Outcomes

We want to provide the business with a model to help accurately determine whether a visa application will be Certified or Denied.

Specifically, we were tasked to:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Identify primary drivers for Certification or Denial.
  • Recommend ideal visa applicant profiles for applications that should be Certified or Denied.
  • Deliver a model that can help accurately predict which visa applicants will be Certified or Denied.

Metric Score Results

  • The final model operates well, with an overall F1 performance score of 83% against training data and 82% against testing data.

  • The Accurancy and Precision metrics are in the mid-to-high 70% range. While lower than the typical 80% target values, these metrics matter less in our scenario. We may have a few more False Positives than desired, but the impact is less than that of False Netsince we do not want to inaccurately certify visa that should have been denied.

  • Recall is high, at 89% against training data and 87% against testing data. The number of False Negatives should be low. This has a high impact, since we want to reduce the number of inaccurate visa Denials.

Standard Error Rates

From our final confusion matrix, we can determine that the model has these error results:

  • True Negative: Correctly predicted Denied, and the application was Denied.

    • Train: 17.01%
    • Test: 15.53%

  • False Negative: Incorrectly predicted Denied, but the application was Certified.

    • Train: 7.19%%
    • Test: 8.06%

  • True Positive: Correctly predicted Certified, and the application was Certified.

    • Train: 59.6%
    • Test: 58.73%

  • False Positive: Incorrectly predicted Certified, but the application was Denied.

    • Train: 16.2%
    • Test: 17.69%

The test results are most critical, as these operated on unseen data.

Here, we see that our model should be able to avoid improperly predicting a visa application as Certified 82.31% of the time (with the 17.69% error rate below) on unseen data.

Similarly, the model should be able to avoid incorrectly predicting a Denial with 91.94% accuracy, based on how it assessed unseen data (with a 8.06% error rate).

The model performs worse on unseen data when it comes to accurately predicting a certification, but since the applications would likely be certified anyway, this is less critical than missing the other two scenarios.

Hypothesis Results

Null Hypothesis:

  • H0: No features have an impact on case status outcomes.

Result: Our research shows that several features have an impact on Case Status outcomes. Therefore, we can reject the Null hypothesis based on evidence presented below.

Alternative Hypothesis:

  • HA: One or more features have an impact on case status outcomes.

Result: Our models clearly detected feature impacts, as noted earlier. So, we can accept the Alternative Hypothesis.

Even though we prioritized F1 originally, this score ended up even higher than our target metric. For our scenario, this is a highly positive outcome for the model.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Business Insights¶

Based on this overall EDA and model analysis, we can gain some valuable insights in our quest to provide the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC) with a machine learning model that can help assess and predict an applicant's case outcome, and maximize internal resource efficiency.

Feature Importance¶

Our models clearly detected several key features that can impact whether a visa application is Certified or Denied.

  • Level of education, specifically High School (33.8% importance, about 1/3 of all feature weights), is by far the most critical feature for determining whether an applicant's visa is Certified.

  • Job experience is the next most important feature (about 20% weight). Applicants with more job experience are nearly twice as likely to have their visa applications Certified.

  • Prevailing Wage is also an important feature (13%).

  • Continent of residence has some value as well. Although the majority of applications are from Asia, two models detected that Europe is also a prime residence for successful visa applicants.

Case Outcomes by Feature¶

As they relate to applications being Certified or Denied, we found several interesting correlations for specific data points. Many of these also surfaced during our model construction, which we'll discuss in more detail later.

Case Status vs. Level of Education

Here, we can observe that the level of education plays a considerable role in case status, both internal to each class of education, and to the overall Certification totals. It is evident that lacking higher education is a key contributor to Denials.

Recommendations¶

Model Deployment¶

The original analysis makes the assumption that F1 scores are most important, giving us the best balance for both accurate Certifications and Denials. The model prepared in this notebook should go into production to immediately help with identifying parameters for Certification or Denial.

Additional hypertuning for individual models could be beneficial as time permits, to increase the model's ability to correctly predict visa outcomes.

Visa Sorting Guidelines¶

The business could implement automated separation of applications into potential Certifications vs. Denials based on setting up ideal and non-ideal rules for applications.

Ideal Visa Applicant Profile¶

An ideal applicant to be Certified has these characteristics, and will likely be Certified:

  • Possesses at least a High School Education, but ideally a Doctorate or Master's Degree.

    • Doctorate: 87% certified, 12% denied
    • Master's: 79% certified, 21% denied
    • Bachelor's: 62% certified, 38% denied

  • Has some preexisting job experience.

    • Has job experience: 74% certified, 26% denied

  • Desired wages are annual, and match the prevailing wage for the occupation/position.

    • Monthly wages: 62% certified, 38% denied
    • Weekly wages: 62% certified, 38% denied
    • Yearly wages: 70% certified, 30% denied

  • Resides in Europe or Africa (although this carries less weight), since applicants from these continents enjoy higher Certification rates and lower Denial rates.

    • Europe: 79% certified, 21% denied
    • Africa: 72% certified, 28% denied

Least Desirable Visa Applicant Profile¶

A less-than-ideal applicant has these characteristics, and will likely be Denied.

  • Possesses only a High School Education.

    • High School: 34% certified, 66% denied

  • Has no preexisting job experience.

    • Lacks job experience: 56% certified, 44% denied

  • Desired wages are below the prevailing wage for the occupation/position, and paid hourly, weekly, or monthly.

    • Hourly wages: 35% certified, 65% denied

  • Resides in North or South America. And while applicants from Oceania and Asia have Certification rates in the 60% range, they both have Denied rates that exceed 30%.

    • South America: 58% certified, 42% denied
    • North America: 62% certified, 38% denied
    • Oceania: 64% certified, 36% denied
    • Asia: 65% certified, 35% denied
